<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910405-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>910405-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Columbia Pictures   Separates Marketing   For Two Movie Units</HL><DATE>04/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   SNE WNEWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>JAPAN (JA)</RE><LP>   CULVER CITY, Calif. -- Columbia Pictures EntertainmentInc. reorganized its marketing operations, establishingseparate departments to market movies produced by itsColumbia Pictures and Tri-Star Pictures units.   Since Sony Corp. acquired the company in 1989, a singlemarketing staff has been responsible for movies produced byboth studios, even though Columbia and TriStar are run bydifferent management teams and are otherwise autonomous. Newmanagement at both units has been beefing up releaseschedules, and &quot;the quality and volume of product from bothColumbia and Tri-Star mandate this new structure,&quot; said SidGanis, executive vice president.</LP><TEXT>   Buffy Shutt and Kathy Jones, who had headed the umbrellamarketing operation for both studios, will now work directlyfor Tri-Star as president of marketing and executive vicepresident, respectively. Both executives, who started atParamount Communications Inc.'s studio and later formed theirown marketing company, joined Columbia prior to the Sonyacquisition. At Tri-Star, they report to Chairman MikeMedavoy.   Columbia, meanwhile, named Kathy Silver president ofmarketing for that unit. Ms. Silver is a movie marketingconsultant who has held marketing and advertising posts atindependent producer Morgan Creek Productions and at TimeWarner Inc.'s Warner Bros. unit. She will report to Columbiastudio chief Frank Price, with whom she has worked as aconsultant on such past films as &quot;Tootsie,&quot; &quot;Ghostbusters&quot;and &quot;Gandhi.&quot;   ---   Corrections andamp; Amplifications                                                                                                          COLUMBIA PICTURES ENTERTAINMENT Inc. named Paula Silverpresident of marketing of its Columbia Pictures studio. InFriday's edition she was incorrectly identified.   (WSJ April 10, 1991)</TEXT></DOC>